Activity description: what were the expectations and what did you do?
For the 2026 CrimsonCode Hackathon at Washington State University, our team participated in a 24-hour development sprint under the theme "Reinventing the Wheel." We identified a modern educational problem that needed reinventing which was the struggle to maintain student engagement in a classroom of digital distractions. Instead of seeing video games as a distraction to learning, we chose to utilize them as the primary vehicle for education.
We developed OceanTown, which is an environmental simulation game designed to teach players about the balance of ecosystems. The application challenges players to manage an island while monitoring three critical measurables: Population, Environment Health, and Happiness. By the end of the event, we delivered a functional web-based simulation where player choices directly impact these measurables, visualizing the real-world consequences of climate change through interactive gameplay.
Technical decisions: what decisions did you take from a technical perspective throughout this activity/event?
Framework Selection: React, TypeScript, Vite
Backend Architecture: C# / ASP.NET Core 
Template Utilization: To maximize our limited time, we started with the Visual Studio React + ASP.NET Core template. This decision allowed us to skip the initial boilerplate setup and move immediately into developing the game’s core environmental logic.
Other: We used a C# backend to handle the simulation logic and data calculations. This allowed us to maintain a clean separation of responsibilities, where the backend serves as the simulation engine calculating the measurables while the frontend acts as the visualization layer. We also integrated ElevenLabs for text to speed dialogue to take into account for accessibility which we won the foundation track with.
